1: Read the data

if (!file.exists("met_all.gz"))
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
    )
met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

2: Prepare the data

data.table::week("2019-08-01 00:00:00")
[1] 31
met %>%
  filter(temp > -17 & elev != 9999) %>%
  mutate(date = ymd_h(paste(year, month, day, hour, sep = " ")),
         week   = data.table::week(date)) %>%
  count(year, month, week) %>%
  arrange(year, month, week)
    year month  week      n
   <int> <int> <int>  <int>

3:  2019     8    33 527880
4:  2019     8    34 523806
5:  2019     8    35 446542
met %>%
  filter(temp > -17
         & elev != 9999.0) %>%
  mutate(date = ymd_h(paste(year, month, day, hour, sep = " ")),
         week = data.table::week(date)) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  filter(week == min(week)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(USAFID) %>%
  summarise(mean_temp = mean(temp),
            mean_rh = mean(rh),
            mean_wind_sp = mean(`wind.sp`), 
            mean_vis_dist = mean(`vis.dist`),
            mean_dew_point = mean(`dew.point`),
            mean_lat = mean(lat),
            mean_lon = mean(lon),
            mean_elev = mean(elev),
            .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(region = case_when(
    mean_lon > -98.00 & mean_lat > 39.71 ~ "NE",
    mean_lon <= -98.00 & mean_lat > 39.71 ~ "NW",
    mean_lon > -98.00 & mean_lat <= 39.71 ~ "SE",
    mean_lon <= -98.00 & mean_lat <= 39.71 ~ "SW"
  ),
  visibility = case_when(
    mean_vis_dist >= 0 & mean_vis_dist < 1000 ~ "fog",
    mean_vis_dist >= 1000 & mean_vis_dist < 6000  ~ "mist",
    mean_vis_dist >= 6000 & mean_vis_dist < 10000 ~ "haze",
    mean_vis_dist >= 10000 ~ "clear"
  ),
  elevation_category = case_when(
    mean_elev >= 252 ~ "high",
    mean_elev <= 252 ~ "low"
  )
  ) -> met_filtered

3: Use geom_violin to examine the wind speed and dew point by region

met_filtered %>%
  select(mean_dew_point, mean_wind_sp, region) %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = c(mean_dew_point, mean_wind_sp), names_to = "var", values_to = "val") %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(x = 1, y = val)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  ggh4x::facet_grid2(
    var ~ region,
    scales = "free_y",
    independent = "y",
    axes = "y",
    switch = "y",
    labeller = labeller(
      var = c(
        mean_dew_point = "Dew Point (Â°C)",
        mean_wind_sp   = "Wind Speed (m/s)"
      )
    )
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        strip.placement = "outside",
        strip.background = element_blank(),
        strip.text.y.left = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "",
       title = "Dew Ponit and Wind Speed Faceted by Regions")

For the NE, SE, and SW regions, the dew point follows a unimodal distribution. Dew points for. NE and SW regions seem to be mostly distributed around the 15Â°C mark. For the SE region, the dew point seems to be mostly distributed around 21Â°C. The NW region interestingly has a bimodal distribution with the primary distribution being weighted aroun 9Â°C and the secondary distribution around 19 Â°C.

The wind speeds for the NE, NW,and SE regions seem to follow a unimodal distribution with the wind speeds being distributed primarily around 1.5, 3, and 1.5 m/s respectively. The SW region has a bimodal wind speed distribution with the wind speed primarily being distributed around 2 mâs and secondarily around 3.75 m/s.

4: Use geom_jitter with stat_smooth to examine the association between dew point and wind speed by region

met_filtered %>%
  select(mean_dew_point, mean_wind_sp, region) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(x = mean_dew_point, y = mean_wind_sp, color = region)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_smooth(aes(linetype = region), method = "lm") +
  facet_wrap( ~ region, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Dew Point (Â°C)",
       y = "Wind Speed (m/s)",
       title = "Correlation between Dew Point and Wind Speed")

Across all four regions, dew point has a weak but positive correlation with wind speed (i.e.Â as dew point increases, wind speed also increases).

5: Use geom_bar to create barplots of the weather stations by elevation category colored by region

met_filtered %>%

  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  group_by(elevation_category, region) %>%
  summarise(n = n_distinct(USAFID), .groups = "drop") %>%

            position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), 
            vjust = -0.3, size = 3) +
  labs(x = "Elevation Categhory (Elevations â¥ 252 m are 'high'; elevations < 252 m are 'low')",
       y = "Number of Stations",
       fill = "Region",
       title = "Counts of Stations at High and Low Elevations by Region")

Among the high elevation stations, the NE has the most stations with 262 stations. For the low elevation stations, the SE region has the most at 502 stations. For both elevation categories, the NW has the least stations.

6: Use stat_summary to examine mean dew point and wind speed by region with standard deviation error bars

met_filtered %>%

7: Make a map showing the spatial trend in relative humidity in the US

colors <- colorFactor(
  palette = c("dodgerblue", "firebrick", "green", "magenta"),
  domain  = factor(met_filtered$region, levels = sort(unique(met_filtered$region)))
)


met_filtered %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_rh)) %>%
  head(10) -> top10_rh

met_filtered %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles('OpenStreetMap') %>% 
  addCircles(lat =~ mean_lat, lng =~ mean_lon, opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1, radius = 500, color = ~colors(factor(region))) %>%
  addMarkers(~top10_rh$mean_lon, ~top10_rh$mean_lat, popup = ~as.character(top10_rh$mean_rh), label = ~as.character(top10_rh$mean_rh)) %>%
  addLegend(
    "bottomright",
    pal = colors,
    values = ~factor(region),
    title = "Region"
  )

The stations with higher relative humidity tend to fall in the coastal or in the northern midwest states. The NW region has 5 of the 10 most humid sites. This is consistent with known weather patterns that characterize the PNW as a generally humid area that receives a lot of rain / snow during the winter months.

8: Use a ggplot extension (Using ggpubr to add r and p values to plot 4)

met_filtered %>%
  select(mean_dew_point, mean_wind_sp, region) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  
  ggplot(aes(x = mean_dew_point, y = mean_wind_sp, color = region)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_smooth(aes(linetype = region), method = "lm") +
  ggpubr::stat_cor(
    aes(x = mean_dew_point, y = mean_wind_sp),
    method = "pearson",
    label.x.npc = "left",
    label.y.npc = "top",
    parse = FALSE,
    label.sep = "\n",
    size = 4,
    color = "black",
    inherit.aes = FALSE
  ) +
  facet_wrap( ~ region, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Dew Point (Â°C)",
       y = "Wind Speed (m/s)",
       title = "Correlation between Dew Point and Wind Speed")

Now that we have p values, we can see that only the SE has a significant, weak positive correlation. All the other regions have p values > 0.05, suggesting that these weak positive correlations are not that robust.
